        <!-- Part 4 -->
        <section id="protocol-wars">
          <div class="font-mono text-sm text-green mb-6">
            <span class="text-secondary">04 //</span> The Protocol Wars: MCP vs A2A
          </div>
          
          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Multi-agent systems need standards for communication. Two protocols have emerged as the dominant contenders, but they solve <strong class="text-foreground">different problems at different layers</strong>. Understanding which to use — and when — is critical.
          </p>

          <!-- Protocol Comparison Diagram -->
          <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
            <p class="text-small font-mono text-green mb-4">$ explain --protocols mcp a2a</p>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
              <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-4">
                <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
                  <div class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-cyan"></div>
                  <p class="font-mono text-foreground font-medium">MCP (Model Context Protocol)</p>
                </div>
                <p class="text-small text-green font-mono mb-2">// Vertical: Agent ↕ Tools</p>
                <div class="space-y-2 text-small text-secondary">
                  <p>Client↔Server bridge for tools</p>
                  <p>Discovery: <code class="px-1 bg-subtle rounded text-xs">tools/list</code></p>
                  <p>Invocation: <code class="px-1 bg-subtle rounded text-xs">tools/call</code></p>
                  <p>Resources + Prompts</p>
                  <p class="text-text-muted mt-2">Answers: "What capabilities exist?"</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-4">
                <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
                  <div class="w-2 h-2 rounded-full bg-green"></div>
                  <p class="font-mono text-foreground font-medium">A2A (Agent-to-Agent)</p>
                </div>
                <p class="text-small text-green font-mono mb-2">// Horizontal: Agent ↔ Agent</p>
                <div class="space-y-2 text-small text-secondary">
                  <p>Agent discovery via Agent Cards</p>
                  <p>Task delegation + negotiation</p>
                  <p>Artifact exchange</p>
                  <p>JSON-RPC / gRPC / HTTP</p>
                  <p class="text-text-muted mt-2">Answers: "How do agents collaborate?"</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            <a href="https://modelcontextprotocol.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-green hover:underline">MCP</a>, introduced by Anthropic, standardizes how any model or agent connects to external tools and data sources. Think of it as the USB standard for AI: a universal connector that lets agents discover and invoke capabilities without hardcoded integrations. An agent can attach to a database MCP server, a GitHub MCP server, and a Slack MCP server — each exposing tools through the same protocol.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            <a href="https://a2aproject.github.io/A2A/latest/specification" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-green hover:underline">A2A</a> solves a different problem: how do agents find and commission work from each other across trust boundaries? Its core concepts — Agent Cards (discoverable at <code class="px-1 py-0.5 bg-subtle rounded text-foreground text-xs">/.well-known/agent.json</code>), Tasks, Messages, and Artifacts — enable cross-organizational agent collaboration.
          </p>

          <!-- Protocol Stack Diagram -->
          <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
            <p class="text-small font-mono text-green mb-4">$ cat protocol_stack.yml</p>
            <div class="font-mono text-sm">
              <div class="border border-border rounded p-3 mb-2 text-center">
                <p class="text-foreground">Application Layer</p>
                <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Your multi-agent system</p>
              </div>
              <div class="flex items-center justify-center text-text-muted mb-2">&#8595;</div>
              <div class="border border-green/50 rounded p-3 mb-2 text-center bg-green/5">
                <p class="text-green">A2A — Agent-to-Agent Protocol</p>
                <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Agent discovery, task delegation, artifact exchange</p>
              </div>
              <div class="flex items-center justify-center text-text-muted mb-2">&#8595;</div>
              <div class="border border-cyan/50 rounded p-3 mb-2 text-center bg-cyan/5">
                <p class="text-cyan">MCP — Model Context Protocol</p>
                <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Tool discovery, invocation, resources, prompts</p>
              </div>
              <div class="flex items-center justify-center text-text-muted mb-2">&#8595;</div>
              <div class="border border-border rounded p-3 text-center">
                <p class="text-secondary">External Systems</p>
                <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Databases, APIs, file systems, SaaS</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed">
            The mental model: <strong class="text-foreground">MCP is the vertical axis</strong> (connecting agents to tools and data), <strong class="text-foreground">A2A is the horizontal axis</strong> (connecting agent runtimes to each other). Teams often use both: MCP for tool integration within a stack, A2A when agents span organizational boundaries.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Part 5 -->
        <section id="skills">
          <div class="font-mono text-sm text-green mb-6">
            <span class="text-secondary">05 //</span> Skills: The New Unit of Intelligence
          </div>
          
          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Models have parameters. Agents have tools. But what makes an agent actually good at a specific task? <strong class="text-foreground">Skills</strong>. A skill is a versionable package of procedural expertise — instructions, scripts, references, and assets centered on a <code class="px-1 py-0.5 bg-subtle rounded text-foreground text-xs">SKILL.md</code> file.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            <a href="https://www.anthropic.com/engineering/equipping-agents-for-the-real-world-with-agent-skills" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-green hover:underline">Anthropic's engineering team</a> frames skills as the bridge between raw model capability and reliable task execution. The <a href="https://agentskills.io/specification" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-green hover:underline">Agent Skills specification</a> formalizes four layers:
          </p>

          <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-6 mb-8">
            <p class="text-small font-mono text-green mb-4">$ cat skill_taxonomy.json</p>
            <div class="space-y-4 font-mono text-sm">
              <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-green shrink-0">L4</span>
                <div>
                  <p class="text-foreground">Policy / Guardrails</p>
                  <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">What must never happen — rules, allowlists, approvals</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l border-border ml-3 h-3"></div>
              <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-green shrink-0">L3</span>
                <div>
                  <p class="text-foreground">Skill / Playbook</p>
                  <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">How to use primitives — SKILL.md, checklists, conventions</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l border-border ml-3 h-3"></div>
              <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-green shrink-0">L2</span>
                <div>
                  <p class="text-foreground">Tool / Integration</p>
                  <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">What primitives exist — MCP servers, REST APIs, DB bindings</p>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div class="border-l border-border ml-3 h-3"></div>
              <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
                <span class="text-green shrink-0">L1</span>
                <div>
                  <p class="text-foreground">Data / Context</p>
                  <p class="text-text-muted text-xs">Ground truth — docs, RAG corpora, runbooks, schemas</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The key innovation is <strong class="text-foreground">progressive loading</strong>. Skills don't dump their entire contents into the agent's context. Instead:
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-3 mb-6">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3 bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-4">
              <span class="text-green font-mono text-sm shrink-0">1</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-small text-foreground font-medium">Always On: Metadata Band</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-secondary">Name + description (~100 tokens). Always present so the agent knows the skill exists.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3 bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-4">
              <span class="text-green font-mono text-sm shrink-0">2</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-small text-foreground font-medium">On Relevance: Full SKILL.md</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-secondary">Agent reads the complete instructions when the task matches the skill's domain.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3 bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-4">
              <span class="text-green font-mono text-sm shrink-0">3</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-small text-foreground font-medium">On Subtask: Deep Resources</p>
                <p class="text-xs text-secondary">references/, scripts/, assets/ loaded only for specific sub-problems.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Platform Comparison -->
          <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
            <table class="w-full text-small border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
              <thead>
                <tr class="bg-elevated">
                  <th class="text-left p-3 font-mono text-green border-b border-border">Dimension</th>
                  <th class="text-left p-3 font-mono text-green border-b border-border">Agent Skills / Claude</th>
                  <th class="text-left p-3 font-mono text-green border-b border-border">Cursor Skills</th>
                  <th class="text-left p-3 font-mono text-green border-b border-border">GPT Actions</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody class="text-secondary">
                <tr class="border-b border-border">
                  <td class="p-3 font-medium text-foreground">Artifact</td>
                  <td class="p-3">SKILL.md + scripts/</td>
                  <td class="p-3">SKILL.md folder</td>
                  <td class="p-3">OpenAPI spec</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-border">
                  <td class="p-3 font-medium text-foreground">Activation</td>
                  <td class="p-3">Model selects via metadata</td>
                  <td class="p-3">Auto or explicit</td>
                  <td class="p-3">Function calling</td>
                </tr>
                <tr class="border-b border-border">
                  <td class="p-3 font-medium text-foreground">Strength</td>
                  <td class="p-3">Deep procedural knowledge</td>
                  <td class="p-3">Repo/workspace integration</td>
                  <td class="p-3">SaaS integration</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td class="p-3 font-medium text-foreground">Composition</td>
                  <td class="p-3">Skill + MCP tools</td>
                  <td class="p-3">Skill + MCP tools</td>
                  <td class="p-3">Chained HTTP calls</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed">
            The convergence is clear: <strong class="text-foreground">skills teach workflow</strong>; <strong class="text-foreground">MCP/APIs supply interfaces</strong>. Organizations are building internal "skill registries" — approved git namespaces with semver tags and SBOM-style audits. Skills are becoming dependencies, managed with the same rigor as npm packages or Python libraries.
          </p>
        </section>

        <!-- Part 6 -->
        <section id="failure-modes">
          <div class="font-mono text-sm text-green mb-6">
            <span class="text-secondary">06 //</span> Why Multi-Agent Systems Break
          </div>
          
          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Multi-agent systems fail in ways that single-agent systems don't. Understanding these failure modes is prerequisite knowledge for anyone building hierarchical architectures.
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
            <!-- Failure Mode 1 -->
            <div class="border-l-2 border-red-500/50 pl-4">
              <h3 class="text-h3 text-foreground mb-2">Coordination Failures</h3>
              <div class="space-y-2 text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed">
                <p><strong class="text-foreground">Partial observability:</strong> Agents can't see each other's full scratchpad. Badly chosen shared state causes either under-sharing (agents block waiting for context) or over-sharing (context rot from irrelevant information).</p>
                <p><strong class="text-foreground">Synchronization:</strong> Parallel workers editing the same codebase need merge semantics — CRDT-like logs, single-writer artifacts, or supervisor arbitration. Without this, you get silent conflicts.</p>
                <p><strong class="text-foreground">Non-determinism:</strong> Different temperatures, tool availability, and prompt variations make replay for debugging nearly impossible without structured traces.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Failure Mode 2 -->
            <div class="border-l-2 border-yellow-500/50 pl-4">
              <h3 class="text-h3 text-foreground mb-2">Trust Failures</h3>
              <div class="space-y-2 text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed">
                <p><strong class="text-foreground">No inherent trust:</strong> Treat another agent's output as untrusted input until validated through schemas, unit tests, retrieval citations, or a second model with a different inductive bias.</p>
                <p><strong class="text-foreground">Monoculture risk:</strong> Using the same model family for planning and verification shares blind spots. If Claude writes code and Claude reviews it, systematic errors pass through. Cross-model judges, static analysis, and code execution are the countermeasures.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Failure Mode 3 -->
            <div class="border-l-2 border-orange-500/50 pl-4">
              <h3 class="text-h3 text-foreground mb-2">Error Cascades</h3>
              <div class="space-y-2 text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed">
                <p><strong class="text-foreground">The cascade pattern:</strong> One wrong intermediate artifact becomes "ground truth" for downstream agents. Conformity bias amplifies the error — subsequent agents are reluctant to contradict their predecessor.</p>
                <p><strong class="text-foreground">Mitigations:</strong> Provenance/lineage tracking on every claim. Edge validators (lightweight checks between agents). Narrow interfaces (structured outputs with schemas). Supervisor gating before merge. OpenTelemetry-style spans per agent/tool invocation.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-6">
            <p class="text-small font-mono text-green mb-4">$ cat error_cascade_flow.txt</p>
            <div class="font-mono text-sm text-secondary">
              <p><span class="text-foreground">Agent_A</span> generates code with subtle bug</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted pl-2">&#8595; <span class="text-yellow-500/80">no edge validator</span></p>
              <p><span class="text-foreground">Agent_B</span> writes tests that pass (tests match the bug)</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted pl-2">&#8595; <span class="text-yellow-500/80">conformity bias</span></p>
              <p><span class="text-foreground">Agent_C</span> reviews and approves (same model, same blind spot)</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted pl-2">&#8595; <span class="text-yellow-500/80">monoculture</span></p>
              <p><span class="text-foreground">Agent_D</span> deploys to production</p>
              <p class="text-text-muted pl-2">&#8595; <span class="text-red-400">cascade complete</span></p>
              <p class="text-red-400 mt-2">// Bug discovered by users, not by the agent system</p>
              <p class="text-green mt-3">// Fix: Cross-model judges + edge validators + provenance</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Part 7 -->
        <section id="developer-role">
          <div class="font-mono text-sm text-green mb-6">
            <span class="text-secondary">07 //</span> The Developer's New Role
          </div>
          
          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            <a href="https://www.idc.com/resource-center/blog/developers-arent-just-using-ai-agents-theyre-building-them/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-green hover:underline">IDC forecasts</a> that by 2030, <strong class="text-foreground">70% of developers will partner with autonomous agents</strong>, shifting emphasis to planning, design, and orchestration. Developers aren't just using AI agents — they're building them.
          </p>

          <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-green pl-4 py-2 mb-6">
            <p class="text-body text-foreground italic">"The new paradigm is characterized by developers who are simultaneously users, creators, and governors of intelligent systems."</p>
            <p class="text-small text-secondary mt-2">— IDC Developer/DevOps FutureScape</p>
          </blockquote>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The skills that matter are shifting. Here's what's rising and what's declining:
          </p>

          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-8">
            <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-5">
              <p class="text-small font-mono text-green mb-3">// Rising</p>
              <div class="space-y-2 text-small text-secondary">
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-green">&#9650;</span> <span class="text-foreground">Task decomposition & delegation</span></p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-green">&#9650;</span> <span class="text-foreground">Verification discipline (evals, static analysis)</span></p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-green">&#9650;</span> <span class="text-foreground">Observability & tracing for agent paths</span></p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-green">&#9650;</span> <span class="text-foreground">Risk literacy (prompt injection, trust)</span></p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-green">&#9650;</span> <span class="text-foreground">Skill authoring & tool engineering</span></p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-green">&#9650;</span> <span class="text-foreground">System design & architecture</span></p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-5">
              <p class="text-small font-mono text-secondary mb-3">// Declining</p>
              <div class="space-y-2 text-small text-secondary">
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">&#9660;</span> Boilerplate code writing</p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">&#9660;</span> Manual test case authoring</p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">&#9660;</span> Configuration management</p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">&#9660;</span> Documentation as afterthought</p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">&#9660;</span> Solo debugging sessions</p>
                <p class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-red-400">&#9660;</span> Manual code review (fully)</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Four new hybrid roles are emerging at the intersection of engineering and AI governance:
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-3">
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-green font-mono text-sm shrink-0 w-6">01</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-body text-foreground font-medium">Skill Author / Technical Writer</p>
                <p class="text-small text-secondary">Encodes institutional knowledge into versionable SKILL.md packages with progressive structure, worked examples, and deterministic scripts.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-green font-mono text-sm shrink-0 w-6">02</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-body text-foreground font-medium">Tooling Engineer</p>
                <p class="text-small text-secondary">Builds MCP servers, designs OpenAPI surfaces, handles auth, ensures idempotent actions, and instruments tool failures with observability.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-green font-mono text-sm shrink-0 w-6">03</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-body text-foreground font-medium">Governance & Security Reviewer</p>
                <p class="text-small text-secondary">Treats skills as dependencies — reviews scripts, audits network calls, checks for instruction injection, monitors data egress paths.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
              <span class="text-green font-mono text-sm shrink-0 w-6">04</span>
              <div>
                <p class="text-body text-foreground font-medium">Evals Owner</p>
                <p class="text-small text-secondary">Designs task suites and rubrics that prove whether a skill, agent, or system actually reduces failures — Anthropic's "start with evaluation" principle.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

        <!-- Part 8 -->
        <section id="building">
          <div class="font-mono text-sm text-green mb-6">
            <span class="text-secondary">08 //</span> Building Your First Hierarchical Agent System
          </div>
          
          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            Theory is useful. Shipping is better. Here's a practical checklist for building your first hierarchical multi-agent system:
          </p>

          <div class="space-y-6 mb-8">
            <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-5">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
                <span class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-green/20 flex items-center justify-center text-green font-mono text-xs">1</span>
                <h3 class="text-h3 text-foreground">Define the Contract</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-3">Every agent boundary needs a typed payload. What goes in, what comes out, what errors look like.</p>
              <div class="bg-subtle rounded p-3 font-mono text-xs text-secondary overflow-x-auto">
                <pre><code set:html={codeContract} /></pre>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-5">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
                <span class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-green/20 flex items-center justify-center text-green font-mono text-xs">2</span>
                <h3 class="text-h3 text-foreground">Pick Topology from Task Structure</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed">Analyze your task dependency graph. Parallelizable subtasks? Use fan-out swarm. Tight dependencies? Pipeline. Complex with quality gates? Hierarchical supervisor. Don't over-architect — start with supervisor and evolve.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-5">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
                <span class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-green/20 flex items-center justify-center text-green font-mono text-xs">3</span>
                <h3 class="text-h3 text-foreground">Attach Tools via MCP</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed">Each agent gets a scoped set of MCP servers. The ImplementAgent gets filesystem + git. The SecurityAgent gets vulnerability scanners. The DeployAgent gets CI/CD APIs. Narrow tool access is scope sanitization in practice.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-5">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
                <span class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-green/20 flex items-center justify-center text-green font-mono text-xs">4</span>
                <h3 class="text-h3 text-foreground">Add a Routing Policy</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed">Start with a static supervisor (explicit rules for delegation). Graduate to bandit-style beliefs when you have enough usage data. The REDEREF pattern works well as a drop-in upgrade — no fine-tuning required.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg p-5">
              <div class="flex items-center gap-2 mb-3">
                <span class="w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-green/20 flex items-center justify-center text-green font-mono text-xs">5</span>
                <h3 class="text-h3 text-foreground">Instrument and Gate</h3>
              </div>
              <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed">Traces on every agent/tool invocation (OpenTelemetry spans). Judges at every handoff boundary. Kill switches for runaway delegation loops. And always — always — a maximum recursion depth.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- LangGraph Example -->
          <div class="bg-elevated border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden mb-6">
            <div class="flex items-center gap-2 px-4 py-2 bg-subtle border-b border-border">
