        <!-- Conclusion -->
        <section class="border-t border-border pt-12">
          <div class="font-mono text-sm text-green mb-6">
            <span class="text-secondary">// </span> Conclusion: The Human in the Loop
          </div>
          
          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The agentic development lifecycle isn't about replacing developers. It's about <strong class="text-foreground">changing what development means</strong>. The developer of 2026 isn't someone who types code all day. They're a conductor of agent orchestras — decomposing problems, designing contracts, verifying outputs, and governing autonomous systems.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The skills that matter have shifted from syntax fluency to system thinking. From writing functions to designing agent hierarchies. From debugging individual lines to tracing multi-agent error cascades. From memorizing APIs to authoring skills that teach agents how to use them.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
            The infrastructure is maturing rapidly. MCP standardizes tool access. A2A enables cross-boundary collaboration. Frameworks like LangGraph, CrewAI, and AutoGen make hierarchical orchestration accessible. Research on agent routing (REDEREF) and topology selection (AdaptOrch) brings rigor to what was previously ad-hoc prompt engineering.
          </p>

          <p class="text-body text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-8">
            But the hardest problem isn't technical. It's organizational. <a href="https://www.idc.com/resource-center/blog/developers-arent-just-using-ai-agents-theyre-building-them/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-green hover:underline">IDC predicts</a> a <strong class="text-foreground">35% increase</strong> in spending on AI governance and monitoring by 2029, driven by multi-agent complexity. Companies that treat agentic systems as "just better autocomplete" will be outpaced by those that embrace the full lifecycle shift: from sequential pipelines to concurrent loops, from static requirements to adaptive bets, from human execution to human governance.
          </p>

          <div class="bg-elevated border border-green/30 rounded-lg p-6">
            <p class="text-small font-mono text-green mb-3">$ echo "TL;DR"</p>
            <div class="space-y-2 text-body text-secondary">
              <p>The future of software engineering is <strong class="text-foreground">not writing code</strong>. It's designing the systems that write, validate, and govern code. Master the ADLC, understand multi-agent topologies, and learn to build trust through evaluation — because the agents are already here, and they're waiting for better orchestration.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </section>

